WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
We welcome you to join us in the discussion, and let's get started.

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Mine name is Hassan, I am the author and maintainer of Plotnine,

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:17.000
a grammar of graphics visualization system in Python.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:23.000
Now, in 2011, we had an election in Uganda.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:29.000
I was not satisfied with the breadth and depth of the analysis that showed up in the media,

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:33.000
and I wanted to know more.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:37.000
So I learned Python and dove into the data.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:42.000
When it got to the visualizations, I felt the experience could be better.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:45.000
I looked around and discovered ggplot2,

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:49.000
an implementation of the grammar of graphics in the R programming language.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:54.000
Now, this was the most elegant idea I had come to know of,

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:56.000
and I wanted to use it in Python.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:59.000
I did not think I could implement it,

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:03.000
but as it was a great idea, and great ideas spread,

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:08.000
I expected someone more capable than me would implement it in Python.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:10.000
So I waited.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:16.000
After two years, something came up in Python,

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:19.000
but I was dispirited when I used it.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:22.000
It was a surface-level imitation of a grammar of graphics.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:27.000
It was like slapping the body of a super car onto a regular car.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:31.000
Nonetheless, I contributed to that effort to make it better,

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:41.000
and in doing so, I gained the confidence that I could implement the grammar of graphics in Python.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:43.000
And I also took ownership of the project.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:47.000
That is how Plot9 came to be.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:52.000
Now, I have stressed the phrase a bunch of times.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:57.000
What is one word that comes to your mind when you hear grammar of graphics?

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:03.000
Take five seconds.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:07.000
If you have struggled to nail down what it evokes, that is okay,

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:10.000
even if you are familiar with the concept.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:12.000
But how about a definition?

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:15.000
What is the grammar of graphics?

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:21.000
Well, this is just a language and rules to make statistical graphics.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:25.000
Probably that doesn't add much understanding,

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:31.000
because it is possible to be able to define an idea yet not understand it,

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:37.000
and the vice versa, to understand an idea yet be unable to define it.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:42.000
But to me, that definition is adjacent to the words

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:47.000
and idea that the words grammar of graphics evoke in my mind,

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:51.000
likely because I am quite familiar with the concept.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:55.000
When I hear language and rules, my mind asks,

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:57.000
how do I put things together?

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:01.000
How do I compose stuff in that system?

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:06.000
And grammar of graphics brings to mind composing visualization.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:10.000
So we are going to explore the power and elegance of a system

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:14.000
that is built to be used through composition of its components.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:19.000
The components are, we have the data, we have the aesthetics,

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:24.000
we have the scales, we have statistics, we have positions,

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:28.000
we have geometric objects, we have facets, we have coordinate system,

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:30.000
we have theming.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:36.000
But we have already acquired a suspicion for premature definitions.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:40.000
So we shall just go along and experience the components directly.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:44.000
But first, let's introduce our data set.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:49.000
We are going to look at a subset of the palmer penguins data set.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:53.000
This is a data set of size measurements of three penguin species

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:57.000
observed on three islands in the Antarctica.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:00.000
Ours is stripped down to these three variables.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:03.000
We have the species, the bill length, and the sex.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:07.000
We are going to take a narrow look at the bill length.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:13.000
Often, we want a graphical summary of a continuous variable.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:16.000
A box plot is an example of such a summary.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:18.000
So let us start with that.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:23.000
First, we import all the components for easy exploration,

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:26.000
then declare a grammar of graphics plot.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:30.000
Looking at the penguins data set in the aesthetics,

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:36.000
we map the y aesthetic to the bill length and add a box plot geometry.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:40.000
We get one box plot for all the penguins.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:43.000
We can add a box plot per species.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:49.000
To do that, we map the x aesthetic to the species.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:57.000
But before we continue, let us stream the x and y keywords.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:01.000
We can do that if they are the first two parameters.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:06.000
If you are coming from ggplot2 and from R,

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:10.000
the most obvious difference that you see and you will experience with plot9

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:16.000
is that the aesthetics are wrapped in strings,

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:19.000
are used strings wrapped in quotation marks.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:20.000
So let's continue.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:26.000
That gives us three box plots, one per species.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:30.000
Let's give the species a different color.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:36.000
So we map the species to the color aesthetics

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:40.000
and we get a different color for each species.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:45.000
Now, coloring by the species does not add any information.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:47.000
We shall change that later.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:50.000
For more information, we can add a mean.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:55.000
Comparing means and medians gives us a simple way to detect skew.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:00.000
To do that, we compute a summary statistic using the mean function,

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:06.000
visualize it as a column geometry, and fill it with color.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:14.000
And we get boxes, two types of boxes, the column box and the box plots.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:20.000
But we still have a lot more information trapped within the individual points,

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:25.000
all the information about the variability of the bill length

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:27.000
is still trapped within the points.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:29.000
Let us visualize them.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:35.000
We add a point geometry for that.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:38.000
The points are over plotted.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:44.000
A common solution to that is to change the opacity to something less than one.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:52.000
We do that, change it to half opacity, 0.5.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:55.000
But that doesn't change much.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:58.000
Maybe add some jitter to it.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:01.000
That is another common solution to over plotting.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:04.000
So we set the position to jitter

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:13.000
and we get something like a strip plot overlaid on top of the box plots.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:18.000
But the distribution is still largely hidden.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:23.000
How about we swap the box plot for a violin?

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:30.000
We replace the box plot geometry with the violin geometry

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:33.000
and we get violins.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:40.000
With that plot, we have lost the precision of the five point summary

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:43.000
that the box plot gives us,

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:46.000
but we have gained a better sense of the distribution.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:50.000
Depending on your context, this may be the right decision.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:53.000
But something isn't right with the points.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:55.000
They are wayward.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:00.000
Imagine if we could squish them into the violins.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:02.000
If there are enough of them,

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:09.000
they could by themselves convey a sense of the distribution like that.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:15.000
Looking at that, we do not really need the violin.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:19.000
In fact, we have danced along the motivation

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:23.000
for a fairly recent type of plot called a Siner plot.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:30.000
It came around in 2017 and there is a geometry for that.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:33.000
GeomSiner.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:38.000
And that gives us information about the density distribution,

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:44.000
the number of points, their variance and outliers amongst them.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:46.000
This plot still isn't perfect.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:48.000
Let us refine it.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.000
We have a rectangular column

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:53.000
because it was easier to use at the time,

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:57.000
but it is displaying a point statistic.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:00.000
So a line segment is a better choice.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:03.000
So we introduce a line segment.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:09.000
We use the same statistic and function as the column.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:11.000
We set the color to black

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:14.000
so that we have black lines for each of the species.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:19.000
Stretch it out to match the width of the column,

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:24.000
which is 90% of the available horizontal space.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:26.000
And the y value is constant.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.000
It is the mean.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:31.000
So the segment aligns with the top of the column.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:34.000
That is some cross-checking.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:39.000
So with that, we are done with the need for the bulky column.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:42.000
So we shall remove it.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:49.000
And we have our Siner plot with black lines for the means.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:53.000
But we also note that the exposition

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:58.000
and the color of the means convey the same information.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:02.000
So the color is redundant, the type of species.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:04.000
We can change that.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:11.000
We shall let the color represent the sex of the penguins.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:13.000
We change that,

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:18.000
and that separates the points for each of the species

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:20.000
along the sexes.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:25.000
And that also introduces another problem.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:30.000
Clearly, for each species,

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:34.000
the different sexes have different means.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:38.000
Let us add segments for those means.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:40.000
Now, this is a mechanical process.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:43.000
We start off with the segment we already have.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:44.000
We copy it.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:46.000
We paste it.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:48.000
We remove the fixed color

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:52.000
to let it inherit the global color for the sex.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:55.000
And the result is,

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:57.000
you can barely tell the difference

00:10:57.000 --> 00:10:59.000
between the two segments.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:04.000
But it gives us means for each of the sexes

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:06.000
for every species.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:10.000
But there's something wrong with that.

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:14.000
The colored segments overlap their territories.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:18.000
They need the same type of positioning

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:24.000
as the scenery geometry and the box plot before it.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:27.000
So the default position for the scenery geometry

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:29.000
is to dodge.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:33.000
That is, not to overlap along the x-axis

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:34.000
in the same layer.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:36.000
We tell the dodging system

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:42.000
that the lines occupy 90% of the available width,

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:46.000
and it does the right thing.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:53.000
And that gives us our nice segments.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:57.000
Now, using the text geometry,

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:05.000
we can add counts to each of the groups,

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:12.000
by the sex for each of the species in the group.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:18.000
We set the label to the number of points in the group,

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:21.000
format it as n equals,

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:23.000
and still with the summary statistic,

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:25.000
we find the lowest point

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:28.000
and set the y-aesthetic to a value

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:30.000
below the minimum calculated.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:32.000
We are doing some math

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:35.000
where we subtract a value of one,

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:39.000
and that should give us text

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:42.000
that does not overlap the points.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:46.000
And what we get is that counts in each group

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:50.000
that are placed at the same precise distance below

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:53.000
the lowest point in each group.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:59.000
And let's make the colors more vibrant.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:03.000
Now, those colors are generated by a default color scale.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:08.000
We can vary the parameters slightly

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:10.000
to give them a pop,

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:14.000
and we get something like that.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:17.000
But our problems have not ended.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:21.000
The colored line segments and the points

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:23.000
are the same color.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:26.000
Let us differentiate them,

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:28.000
though the difference has to be small

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:32.000
because they represent the same group.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:38.000
We want the colors to be close enough in space,

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:42.000
so we have to do color math

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:45.000
just like we have done position math

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:48.000
to have the text for the counts

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:51.000
come in below the lowest point.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:54.000
And that color math is going to be

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:56.000
to darken the colors.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:58.000
We use this utility function

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:02.000
which takes a list of colors

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
and some factor,

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:07.000
and it darkens them by that factor.

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:13.000
For example, on the right,

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:15.000
you can see the top.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:18.000
We convert...

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:23.000
We transform the list of colors at the top

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:26.000
by various factors,

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:30.000
and the results are what you see.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:32.000
At the bottom, a factor of one

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:34.000
turns any color black.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:38.000
Using this function

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:42.000
for the desired line segments,

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:48.000
we darken them by a factor of 0.25,

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:50.000
and we have our final plot.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.000
And there we are.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:54.000
We have easily stacked point geometries

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:57.000
and adjusted their positions and colors.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:00.000
In the process, created a visualization

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:03.000
that we can at best call a scene plot

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:05.000
because that is the most complex

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:07.000
of its component geometries.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:09.000
Otherwise, it has no name.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:11.000
It was not repackaged.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:14.000
The grammar of graphics made it easy to compose.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:17.000
Specifically, the layered grammar of graphics

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:19.000
made it easy to compose.

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:21.000
Our first task has been

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:25.000
to get to grips with the concept.

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:27.000
As you have seen it from my perspective,

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:30.000
the next question is a little different.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:34.000
If you know something about the grammar of graphics,

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:36.000
what question...

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:39.000
That question could go like this.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:43.000
Can the grammar of graphics help me with my problem?

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:46.000
The next example is inspired by GitHub user,

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.000
Jonathan Vitale, who asked for help

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:51.000
to create graphics for a guitar scale trainer

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:53.000
using Plot9.

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:55.000
Again, we start with the data,

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:58.000
which is called the data to be visualized.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:00.000
It will look like that.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.000
For each string, a fret to hold down

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:04.000
while plucking the string.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:06.000
But this is the user-friendly format.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:10.000
We have a function that turns it into a format

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:13.000
that is friendly for plotting.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:16.000
Since we are going to be looking at a guitar fret board,

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:20.000
let us define our plotting function.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:22.000
We give it data.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:24.000
It plots something like that.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:26.000
That is our starting point.

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:28.000
We stretch...

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:31.000
We can edit the theme to stretch it out,

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:35.000
give it funky color, remove the grid marks,

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:38.000
and it's starting to take shape.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:41.000
We add some markings within the canvas

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:44.000
and the standard dots,

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:47.000
then the frets, then the strings.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:49.000
We add diameters.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:52.000
We give it an accurate gauge.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:54.000
If you are familiar with guitars,

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:58.000
you may know what that is.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:02.000
For convenience, we bundle all this into a list.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:08.000
We get a template.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:10.000
Everything up to that point has been familiar.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:13.000
We did that in the first part, which is composing.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:15.000
But what makes this interesting

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:18.000
is to get an accurate representation of a guitar.

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:20.000
We have to create a custom scale.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:22.000
That means we have to use some math,

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:27.000
the same math that guitar makers use to create guitars.

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:31.000
The key requirements for a custom scale are the domain,

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:33.000
knowing the domain of the data,

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:39.000
our guitar scale will have 22 frets,

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:42.000
a transformation function,

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:46.000
and an inverse function,

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:50.000
and how to calculate the breaks.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:54.000
Using the Mizani package, which is a key requirement for Port 9,

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:56.000
we create a trans object,

00:17:56.000 --> 00:18:00.000
which is like filling in a template.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:08.000
And after the...

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:14.000
Sorry, that trans object did not appear,

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:16.000
but we use it to create a scale,

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:25.000
and we get the frets unevenly distributed

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:30.000
to show the non-linearity of a guitar scale.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:37.000
And with that, we get to visualize the final chord

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:39.000
that we are going to be looking at,

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:41.000
which is the C major chord.

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:45.000
And those are the geoms that visualize the chord.

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:49.000
And thank you.

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:55.000
applause

